                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d528">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">702.6282/26a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hibbard</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-07-13T21:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 13, 1942—9 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>180. In your forthcoming discussion with President Barclay, you should request
                    that arrangements be made to terminate the code privileges of the German Consul
                    at the same time that the latter receives notice of the Liberian Government’s
                    decision to ask him to leave the country. Several days would doubtless elapse
                    before transportation could be provided for the Consul and his staff, and for
                    obvious reasons we consider it essential that he should not be able to send code
                    messages during that period.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
